Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels – In most of the past decade, central banks have made limited progress in curbing the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero while also engaging in unprecedented expansion of its balance sheet through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed in the footsteps of the Federal Reserve, implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But prices have not reasonably risen anywhere.
Despite these countries all being under deflationary pressure, their monetary policies – as well as their economic performances – are diverging.
The US and UK now have sufficiently strong growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the Eurozone and Japan continue to implement QE, pushing long-term policy rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this difference?
A simple answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have been running persistent current account deficits, making them debtor nations, while the Eurozone and Japan have been running persistent current account surpluses, making them creditor nations.
Negative interest rates are beneficial to debtors but detrimental to creditors, thus the introduction of negative interest rates after the global economic crisis stimulated the recovery of the US and the UK, but had little effect on the euro zone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
As of now, almost all developed countries with large current account surpluses – such as Denmark and Switzerland – have negative interest rates, not just long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also medium-term bonds.
This is definitely not a good thing.
Despite the minimal effect of low interest rates, these central banks still maintain this policy.
If you point out that QE or cutting rates won't bring benefits to the economy, they will divert attention, arguing that raising rates could stimulate the economy --- superficially, it's hard to refute.
But in fact, it is full of loopholes.
The concept of a "backwards-bending savings supply curve" is often mentioned in introductory economics courses: in a certain environment, a decrease in interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because a reduction in interest rates has reduced the income of savers, they will reduce their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
All of these are not negating a general rule—that it forms the basis of modern monetary policy—that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
The impact varies due to the different debt conditions of each economy.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, thus, regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
However, in an economy with a large amount of net foreign asset positions, creditors will naturally be more than debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is the reverse.
Therefore, the effects of the floor rate monetary policy are different between debt and credit economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, because foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, foreign assets of major industrialized economies are large and becoming increasingly diversified today, partly because of the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage continues to increase at the national level.
Despite frequent project imbalances, they have eased somewhat since the start of the financial crisis, but have not been reversed.
This implies that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor status, and that diverges from deficit economies.
Some major commodity exporters, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have had large current account surpluses during times of high oil prices, and have been a notable exception to foreign asset diversification.
Since June 2014, the world oil price experienced a sharp decline, turning the wealth trend of these countries around.
Their export earnings have sharply decreased, with many countries losing half, forcing them to run deficits, relying on massive sovereign wealth funds built up during the global boom in commodities.
Significant reductions in expenditure have become unavoidable now.
Industrialized economies face fundamentally different challenges.
It's a luxury problem, in a sense, to ensure that consumers spend the unexpected windfall from lower import prices.
However, in creditor nations, negative interest rates seem not to have advanced this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This differentiation also exists within the Eurozone.
Despite being a creditor economy as a whole, the eurozone also has debtor countries.
Debt-based economies, such as Spain and Portugal, are currently experiencing frequent surpluses and gradually reducing their debt.
However, the large current account surplus of traditional debtor countries continues to increase the asymmetry between debtor countries and creditor countries.
What's most noteworthy is that since the financial crisis broke out, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, implying that the surplus Germany has accumulated over this period exceeds its total historical sum.
According to current trends, Germany's debt may rise from 60% of its GDP to 100%.
The Governor of the Central Bank should be patient.
In reality, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors tend to be less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bankers seem to be running out of patience, struggling to cope with low inflation, despite output gaps being gradually closed, with the US and Japan also achieving full employment.
Central Bank Governors of debt-ridden countries must stop manipulating the economy with more loose monetary policies that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow themselves to recover, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effect of the oil price decline to disappear.
European Central Bank President Draghi recently admitted that the current monetary policy may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the old ways is not the solution.
